# Localization & RTL

REGO is **Arabic-first and RTL**. English is a secondary locale. Every user-facing
string is localized — no hardcoded text in widgets, ever.

## Setup (already wired)

- `flutter_localizations` + `intl`; codegen config in `l10n.yaml`.
- ARB files in `lib/l10n/` — `app_ar.arb` (Arabic) + `app_en.arb` (English template carrying `@key` metadata).
- Generated `AppLocalizations` → `package:rego/l10n/app_localizations.dart` (gitignored; run `flutter gen-l10n`).
- `MaterialApp` pins `locale: Locale('ar')` and uses `AppLocalizations.localizationsDelegates` / `supportedLocales`.

## Rules

- Add every key to **both** `app_en.arb` (with an `@key` description) and `app_ar.arb`, then run `flutter gen-l10n`.
- Read strings via `AppLocalizations.of(context).<key>` — never string literals inside `build()`.
- Use ICU placeholders for variables, plurals, genders, dates — never string concatenation.
- Never hardcode `TextDirection`. Let the locale drive it; branch on `Directionality.of(context)` only if unavoidable.
- Use **directional** APIs: `EdgeInsetsDirectional` (start/end), `AlignmentDirectional`, `BorderRadiusDirectional` — not `left`/`right`.
- Directional icons (back arrows, chevrons) must mirror. Prefer auto-mirroring icons (`Icons.arrow_back`) over hardcoded glyphs.

## BiDi — mixing Arabic with Latin / numbers

- "REGO", phone numbers, plate codes, etc. are LTR runs inside RTL text.
- Prefer **separating** the Latin token into its own widget over inline mixing.
- When inline mixing in one string is required, wrap the LTR run in Unicode **isolates** `⁦…⁩` (FSI…PDI) or use `intl`'s `Bidi` helpers. Do **not** scatter raw RLM/LRM marks.
- Format numbers/dates with `intl` (`NumberFormat`/`DateFormat`, `ar` locale). Decide deliberately between Western (0-9) and Eastern-Arabic (٠-٩) digits — pick one and be consistent.

## Typography

- Font is **Tajawal** (bundled, see pubspec `fonts`). Never apply negative `letterSpacing` to Arabic text.

## Testing

- Pump screen tests under `Locale('ar')` (RTL) at minimum; ideally assert both `ar` and `en`.
